00:08:33.200 --> 00:08:40.159
if you have the same problems as me, solve one of your problems as well. So what is R in production?

00:08:40.159 --> 00:08:45.280
So I think of it, I'm not entirely sure what it is yet, but I can tell you what it's not. So

00:08:45.280 --> 00:08:51.039
typically when you're putting code in production, it's code that's sufficiently important that

00:08:51.039 --> 00:08:55.599
you're not going to run it just once. You're going to run it maybe again and again and again. Maybe

00:08:55.599 --> 00:09:00.719
that's because you've got a new data set coming in every now and then, or maybe it's because you've

00:09:00.719 --> 00:09:08.080
got new data coming in every day and you want to run your quarter document, produce a dashboard,

00:09:08.080 --> 00:09:13.359
and then send that to your boss every, maybe every Monday morning. So your code is not going

00:09:13.359 --> 00:09:18.960
to be run just once, but it's going to be run multiple times, you know, potentially over,

00:09:18.960 --> 00:09:23.119
you know, months or years. And that's going to introduce some problems and that's going to do

00:09:23.119 --> 00:09:27.520
some challenges, both in the way that you think about your code and the things you need to do in

00:09:27.520 --> 00:09:35.440
your code. The other thing that's really important about in production is that code in production

00:09:35.440 --> 00:09:41.119
is typically not going to be running on just your computer. It's going to be running on a server

00:09:41.119 --> 00:09:46.640
somewhere. And so there's, I think a couple of differences there. The first is if you're using

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:52.320
Windows, that server is almost certainly going to be a Linux machine. And there are a bunch of

00:09:52.320 --> 00:09:57.280
differences between small, but annoying differences between Windows and Linux that you're going to need

00:09:57.280 --> 00:10:02.960
to learn about. It's also typically going to be configured as a server versus your personal

00:10:02.960 --> 00:10:08.960
desktop. So your personal desktop probably uses the language that you speak. It probably uses the

00:10:08.960 --> 00:10:14.640
time zone that you're in. And when you move to using a server, it's going to be using probably

00:10:14.640 --> 00:10:21.359
English or the ASCII locale, and it's going to be using some standard time zone. The other big

00:10:21.359 --> 00:10:25.520
challenge with running code on another computer is what happens when something goes wrong.

00:10:26.320 --> 00:10:32.080
Like it's hard enough to debug your own code on your own computer, when you can kind of put a

00:10:32.080 --> 00:10:36.000
browser statement in, you can do some little interactive experiments and figure out what's

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:42.080
going on. But now your code is running somewhere that you can't interact with. And typically it's

00:10:42.080 --> 00:10:48.000
going to take, you know, maybe five or 10 or 30 minutes to do an iterative cycle. And that's long

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:52.960
enough that half the time, you know, you send the code off to run, you go and do something else,

00:10:52.960 --> 00:10:57.679
and then you've like forgotten what you're doing when you come back to it. So that's the second

00:10:57.679 --> 00:11:03.119
challenge. It's not running just on your computer. And the third challenge is typically in production,

00:11:03.119 --> 00:11:07.599
your code isn't just, it's not just you working on it, it's a team of people. You've got a bunch

00:11:07.599 --> 00:11:12.159
of data scientists colleagues who ideally need to be able to understand your code and you need to

00:11:12.159 --> 00:11:17.520
be able to share work with. But also, you know, you've got, you might be getting data that's

00:11:17.520 --> 00:11:23.440
produced by data engineers in your organization. You might be producing some kind of API that other

00:11:23.440 --> 00:11:29.039
developers in your organization are going to use to get model predictions from. And you're

00:11:29.039 --> 00:11:33.840
certainly going to be sending the results of your analyses, whether those are quarter reports or

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:40.159
shiny apps or something else to the decision makers. And those introduce another set of challenges.

